<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nazarbayev Meets German Communications Industry Delegation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nazarbayev Meets German Communications Industry Delegation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106164394 Almaty Kazakh Radio Network in Kazakh 1400 GMT 
21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2106164394 </F>
<F P=104>  Almaty Kazakh Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Kazakh </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Nursultan Nazarbayev met at his residence 
today with representatives of leading German communications 
companies--Alkatel-Stel, ERST, and Bundes-Os Telecom. They have 
been working in Kazakhstan for three years in accordance with 
agreements that were signed as a part of a German credit line. 
They are building international, intercity, and local telephone 
exchanges in 10 regions of our republic. 
  Last year, such exchanges were built in Zhezkazgan, Arkalyk, 
Aktau, and Kostanau. They are assembling equipment in 
Petropavlovsk, Kokshetau, Karaganda, Shymkent, and 
Ust-Kamenogorsk. A satellite direct communication line has been 
built recently to connect Akmola and Frankfurt-on-Main. They 
familiarized the president with the results of their activities 
in Kazakhstan and suggested a draft plan for joint work in 
future. According to the business representatives, the 
communications system in Kazakhstan must be privatized. The 
earlier it happens, the bigger the profit will be for the 
republic. 
  Telecom, a joint Kazakhstan-German venture, has been set up. 
It installs electronic international switchboard systems. The 
German side also spoke about the increase in investments to the 
republic. Nazarbayev assured German representatives of his 
support. With regard to the privatization of communications 
systems, the president said that an international tender is due 
to be announced soon for the right of foreign companies to 
cooperate with enterprises of this branch of industry. He 
expressed hope that German companies will participate in the 
tender. 
  Also attending the meeting were Prime Minister Sergey 
Tereshchenko and Foreign Minister Saudabayev. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

