<H3> <TI>   Tehran Talks `Proceeding With Difficulty' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tehran Talks `Proceeding With Difficulty' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106215194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1552 
GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2106215194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Oleg Kuzmin] </F>
  [Text] Tehran, 21 Jun -- The participants in the second 
round of Tajik talks, which began on Saturday [18 June], 
completed their fourth day in the Iranian capital today. There 
were two sessions -- one in the morning and one in the evening. 
If the discussion on the draft agreement on a cease-fire for 
the duration of the talks, as proposed by Romero Piriz Ballon, 
the UN secretary general's special envoy, had yielded some 
positive results, it was expected that a plenary meeting would 
have ensued, with foreign observers taking part. 
  However, the ITAR-TASS correspondent has learned from Otahon 
Latifi, the head of the Tajik opposition's delegation, that the 
talks are proceeding with difficulty; the sides have been slow 
in moving from one point to the next and have been groping for 
points of contact. But that is no reason for pessimism, Latifi 
said. 
  Labor Minister Shukurjon Zuhurov, leading the Tajik 
Government delegation, confirmed that the sides have thus far 
discussed only the "first paragraphs" of the UN draft. He said, 
however, that the atmosphere at the talks gives reason to feel 
some restrained optimism. 
  The talks between the Tajik delegations will continue 
tomorrow. The UN envoys will take part in them. 

</TEXT>

