<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Duma Fails To Adopt 1994 Federal Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    State Duma Fails To Adopt 1994 Federal Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206100894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0915 
GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2206100894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Kuznetskov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 22 Jun -- The law on the federal budget for 
1994 was not adopted as a whole today by the State Duma. Before 
the vote on this issue, Mikhail Zadornov, the chairman of the 
Duma's Committee for the Budget, Taxation, Banks, and Finances, 
said that all the amendments that had been made to it during the 
second reading had been taken into account for the document's 
third reading. He noted that these amendments related, in 
particular, to increased spending on defense and fundamental 
science and also to a 15 percent cut in spending on the 
structure of state administration. The deputy stressed that the 
document had undergone a final expert legal and linguistic 
examination. 
  After this, Ivan Rybkin, the chairman of the lower house of 
the Federal Assembly, informed deputies that the third reading 
of this document did not stipulate a debate and he proposed that 
they vote on it as a whole. However, only 194 deputies voted 
for the 1994 budget, while a total of 225 votes was needed for a 
positive outcome. 
  Deputies then left for a break, just prior to the 
announcement of which Rybkin noted that deputies would resume 
the debate on the 1994 budget on their return to the hall. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

