<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister, U.S. Envoy Discuss Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Minister, U.S. Envoy Discuss Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106201694 Tbilisi Radio Tbilisi Network in Georgian 1800 
GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2106201694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tbilisi Radio Tbilisi Network </F>
<F P=105>  Georgian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] This information came from the Defense Ministry 
press service. 
  On 21 June, Lieutenant General Vardiko Nadibaidze, defense 
minister of the Republic of Georgia, received Kent Brown, U.S. 
ambassador to Georgia, who was accompanied by high-ranking 
officials from the U.S. Department of Defense. The meeting was 
attended by Major General Nodar Tatarashvili, chief of the 
General Staff. 
  The defense minister told guests about changes in the Armed 
Forces, which had begun following his appointment as minister. 
The main purpose of these changes is to create a small but 
capable and modern Georgian Army. In order to attain this 
difficult objective, we are receiving a great deal of assistance 
from our partners--the command of the Russian troops in the 
Transcaucasus. However, we would also be pleased to receive 
assistance from our U.S. colleagues and are ready to cooperate 
with them within the framework of NATO's Partnership for Peace 
program in order to safeguard peace in the region, Nadibaidze 
said. 
  At the end of the meeting, the minister thanked guests for 
the visit and for the attention that the United States was 
giving to Georgia and its army construction, adding that 
contacts between the the two countries' military would develop 
further. 

</TEXT>

