<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton Riga Trip Unlikely To Impact Troop Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Clinton Riga Trip Unlikely To Impact Troop Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2106130394 Tallinn BNS in English 0854 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2106130394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, June 21, RIA-BNS -- "I don't believe U.S. 
President Bill Clinton's upcoming visit to Riga is likely to 
speed up the withdrawal of Russian troops from Estonia," 
Estonian President Lennart Meri said in an interview with the 
Russian RIA news agency. 
  In the president's opinion, the Russian leadership has long 
ago adopted a political decision in this question. "It would be 
incorrect on my part to consider President Clinton's visit to 
Riga as putting pressure on the world power called the Russian 
Federation," Meri emphasized. 
  Clinton is going to pay July 6 a six-hour visit to the 
Latvian capital, Riga, during which he is scheduled to meet with 
Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis and his Estonian and Lithuanian 
counterparts, Meri and Algirdas Brazauskas. 
  Estonian Ambassador to the United States Toomas Hendrik 
Ilves 
told BNS Clinton had first mentioned his wish to visit the 
Baltic states last September when he met with the three Baltic 
presidents in New York. 
  White House officials unfortunately dropped Estonia from 
Clinton's schedule after familiarizing themselves with the 
blueprints of the Tallinn Airport: the airfield didn't have a 
runway long enough to receive Air Force One. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

