<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Varennikov Claims Gorbachev Ill in Aug 1991 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Varennikov Claims Gorbachev Ill in Aug 1991 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206083794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0816 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2206083794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Yuriy Shcherban] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 22 TASS -- A leader of the abortive 
Soviet coup of 1991 insisted on Wednesday that former Soviet 
President Mikhail Gorbachev was ill at the time. 
  "In August 1991 Mikhail Gorbachev was badly ill both in the 
physical and morally-psychologic aspects," former Soviet Deputy 
Defence Minister Valentin Varennikov told the trial on Wednesday. 
  Varennikov is the only coup organiser who rejected the 
Duma-proclaimed amnesty and insisted that his case be 
investigated by court. 
  Gorbachev's alleged illness was used by the coup plotters to 
explain the isolation of the president. Gorbachev himself had 
rejected the allegations. 
  Varennikov admitted that communications with the state 
residence in Foros in the Crimea where Gorbachev was staying had 
been cut off, but explained it by the desire not to disturb the 
president during his talks with the coup plotters. 
  "Constant calls could have distracted Gorbachev" from talks 
with the ringleaders who arrived to Foros to get a go-ahead from 
the president for the introduction of a state of emergency in 
the country. 
  Varennikov rejected the accusation that the communications 
had been cut off to isolate Gorbachev. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

