<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dmitriy Semenov Heads New `Lefsha' Party </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dmitriy Semenov Heads New `Lefsha' Party </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106152494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0957 
GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2106152494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, 21 Jun (ITAR-TASS) -- A party with an 
unusual name -- "Lefsha" [left-hander] -- has been registered at 
Russia's Justice Ministry. Dmitriy Semenov, the president of 
the new political association, told ITAR-TASS that: The party 
intends to defend the interests of qualified wage labor workers. 
It consists of qualified industrial and agricultural workers, 
scientific-technical and cultural intelligentsia, students, and 
professional military. 
  We are for forming a middle class in Russia, which, as is 
known, consists not only of medium and small owners but what is 
more important, of qualified and highly-paid workers, the 
party's president said. 
  In keeping with its program, the party will seek to gain 
power constitutionally, in order to carry out a realistic reform 
in the interests of wage labor workers. The aim of the party is 
a legislative reform of social and labor relations. 
  The party has started preparations for its nationwide 
congress, which is to take place at the end of 
September-beginning of October 1994. 

</TEXT>

