<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-120 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  21 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shushkevich Defends Role in Breakup of Former USSR </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shushkevich Defends Role in Breakup of Former USSR </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106143194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0851 
GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2106143194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by BELINFORM correspondent Larisa Lazar for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Minsk, 21 Jun -- Either we choose the road of normal 
economic reforms, or we will remain a third-rate country, 
Stanislav Shushkevich, one of the candidates for the presidency 
of the Republic of Belarus and former head of parliament, said 
at a meeting with war and labor veterans. 
  The candidate expounded on his economic program, which 
envisages bringing the rate of inflation down to 6-10 percent by 
the end of the year (whereas now it stands at over 50 percent). 
  Those attending the meeting were also interested in problems 
connected with the breakup of the Soviet Union. Many people, 
particularly the older generation, are criticizing the former 
speaker, claiming that the USSR was destroyed at Belovezhskaya 
Pushcha. 
  Answering his critics, Stanislav Stanislavavich noted that 
the Soviet Union had in effect broken up before the meeting of 
the leaders of the Slav states at Viskuli. He reminded them 
that seven republics -- Lithuania, Latvia, Estonia, Armenia, 
Georgia, Azerbaijan, and Moldova -- had not taken any part in 
the referendum on the future of the USSR, thereby expressing 
their negative attitude to the empire. Kazakhstan conducted its 
referendum with a different wording. Over 90 percent of 
residents in Ukraine voted for sovereignty. 
  In the opinion of Shushkevich, it was for this very reason 
that an attempt was made at Viskuli to preserve economic ties 
between the Republics and to give them a new impetus through the 
creation of the Commonwealth of Independent States. The 
presidential candidate believes that this averted a "Yugoslav 
scenario," which could well have taken much more dangerous forms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

