<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Forged' Pro-Kebich Article Appears in State-Funded Press </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Forged' Pro-Kebich Article Appears in State-Funded Press </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2106115094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 21 Jun 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> MK2106115094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Valentin Zhdanko: "Election Scandals Over </F>
Shooting on Roads and in the Press"] 
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] Yet another resounding 
scandal in recent days stems from the appearance in three major 
republic papers financed from the state budget of a wide-ranging 
article allegedly reprinted from the Dutch AMSTERDAMGUFIRE [as 
transliterated]. The article takes a negative view of all the 
presidential candidates except Vyacheslaw Kebich. Especially 
many harsh words and offensive hints are leveled at ex-Speaker 
Stanislaw Shushkevich. Mr. Shushkevich's initiative group sent 
an official question to the Dutch Embassy in Warsaw. It 
received the answer: No publication by this name exists in 
Holland, and there have been no such articles in the Dutch 
press. The identity of the author of the forged article remains 
a riddle. 
  The Oversight Council consisting of independent experts 
recommended that in the days remaining before the elections the 
mass media refrain from publishing sociological surveys because, 
the council thought, sociological services in the country are as 
a rule controlled by the government and some of its leaders are 
members of Mr. Kebich's initiative group. This decision evoked 
a negative reaction from official sociologists. According to 
their polls, Mr. Kebich has enjoyed unequaled popularity in the 
republic for a long time now, although observers believe that 
the real mood among the bulk of the population creates some 
doubt that the prime minister will win the 23 June elections. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

