<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Protocol' on NATO-Russia Partnership for Peace Program </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Protocol' on NATO-Russia Partnership for Peace Program </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206133194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1225 
GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2206133194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Protocol on results of discussions between Andrey Kozyrev, </F>
the Russian Foreign Minister, and the NATO Council" -- ITAR-TASS 
headline] 
  [Text] Brussels, 22 Jun 1994 -- 1. Russia and NATO have a 
significant contribution to make to guaranteeing European 
stability and security. Constructive relations of cooperation 
between Russia and NATO, based on mutual respect, advantage, and 
friendship, are therefore a key element in security and 
stability in Europe and accord with the interests of all other 
states in the CSCE region. 
  Russia and NATO welcome the progress that has already been 
achieved in their relations, including that within the framework 
of the North Atlantic Cooperation Council, and they will strive 
to strengthen it further. 
  2. Russia's signing of Partnership for Peace opens up big 
new 
opportunities for the development of relations by means of 
practical cooperation in spheres covered by the framework 
document of Partnership for Peace. 
  Russia and NATO have agreed to prepare a wide-ranging, 
individual program of partnership, in keeping with Russia's 
size, importance and potential. 
  3. They have agreed to establish far-reaching Russia-NATO 
cooperation relations both within and outside the framework of 
Partnership for Peace. These relations, aimed at strengthening 
mutual confidence and openness, will develop to reflect common 
goals and supplement and strengthen relations with all other 
states. They are not directed against the interests of third 
countries and will be transparent. 
  4. Russia and NATO have agreed on broad and in-depth 
dialogue and cooperation in those areas where Russia can make a 
unique and important contribution commensurate with its weight 
and responsibility as a major European, world and nuclear power: 
  -- by exchanging information on security policy problems of 
European dimension; 
  -- by holding, as required, political consultations on 
issues 
of mutual interest; 
  -- by cooperating on the entire range of security issues, 
including, as required, in the sphere of peace-keeping. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

