<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Russia-NATO Program' Not To Be Signed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Russia-NATO Program' Not To Be Signed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2106172194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1542 GMT 21 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2106172194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev has 
declared that the protocol to the Russia-NATO program due to be 
approved in Brussels is not going to be signed. 
  Answering a question from Interfax before his departure for 
Brussels on Tuesday he said the protocol does not require 
signing. "It registers the understanding that Russia and NATO 
are going to cooperate on key elements of the program the 
Russian Defence Minister Pavel Grachev submitted to the NATO 
headquarters about a month ago", Kozyrev said. 
  According to him, Grachev described the military aspects of 
cooperation. "Now we are going to add a political element and 
officially proclaim the cooperation of Russia and NATO," Kozyrev 
said adding that he would sign the Partnership for Peace program 
in Brussels. "We welcome this program too", he said. 
  The minister stressed that the protocol and program 
supplement, not contradict each other. 
  According to Kozyrev, the protocol which is now getting its 
final touch reflects the special relationship of Russia and NATO 
and their potentials. "The interaction and mutually- beneficial 
cooperation of Russia and NATO are possible and necessary", the 
minister reiterated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41127 </DOCNO>
