<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   ITAR-TASS Carries Press Review for 23 Jun </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ITAR-TASS Carries Press Review for 23 Jun </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306053894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0436 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2306053894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Press Review" -- ITAR-TASS headline] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 23 ITAR-TASS -- The Russian national 
press today leads with reports about the signing by Russian 
Minister of Foreign Affairs Andrey Kozyrev in Brussels of the 
Partnership for Peace framework document and of the bilateral 
protocol "Russia and NATO". 
  ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI says in its comment on the event that it 
took place, symbolically, on June 22, the anniversary of the 
beginning of the Great Patriotic War which resulted in the split 
of the world into two opposing camps. By becoming the West's 
partner in European and global security, Russia cleared yet 
another barrier on its way to the civilised world community". 
  "Moscow has secured a special relationship with the West," 
according to NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA. In its analysis of the 
documents signed by the Russian minister of foreign affairs, the 
newspaper says: "It appears that the key phrase of the 
(Russia-NATO) protocol is "Russia and NATO agree to prepare an 
extensive individual programme of partnership which is in line 
with Russia's size, significance and potential". This means 
that Moscow has finally got what it wanted and NATO has 
recognised Russia's "special status". 
  TRUD stresses that "the move enables this country to take a 
more active part in European affairs, including defence. By 
joining the Partnership for Peace programme, Russia avoided the 
danger of finding itself in a sort of isolation from the further 
development of military and political cooperation on the 
European continent". 
  KRASNAYA ZVEZDA writes: "The most important thing is that 
the 
realisation of the Partnership for Peace programme will bridge 
for Russia and NATO the gap which separated Europe a few years 
ago. Another bridge will be provided by the agreement on 
partnership and cooperation between Russia and the European 
Union, which President Boris Yeltsin of the Russian Federation 
is due to sign on the Greek island of Corfu, where a summit of 
the European Union member countries will take place on June 24. 
When the agreement takes effect, it will open up a new, much 
more extensive potential for cooperation between Russia and the 
European Union in the economic and political fields. 

</TEXT>

