<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Fails To Approve Budget at Third Reading </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Fails To Approve Budget at Third Reading </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206172594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1522 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2206172594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On Wednesday the Russian State Duma failed to 
approve the 1994 federal budget at third reading even though it 
was put to a vote three times. 
  During the last round in the evening, 212 votes were cast 
for 
the budget, 43 against with 60 abstentions. Approval required 
225 votes. 
  Acting Minister of Finance Sergey Dubinin did not succeed in 
persuading the Duma to pass the budget as a compromise reached 
in close cooperation between the government and the lower house 
of parliament. He said that without an approved budget the 
government does not have the right to use credits of the Central 
Bank but is limited to taxes which he said constitute only 60 
pct of the necessary resources. This threatens this year's 
supplies to North Russia and the gathering of the harvest and 
puts off the planned raise in the earnings of government 
employees. 
  After the voting results were announced the Agrarian faction 
suggested putting off the matter till Friday as 15 of its 
members were absent. 
  Duma Speaker Ivan Rybkin gave instructions to cancel all 
deputy business trips and visits of parliamentary delegations 
and said that all deputies should come to Moscow for the crucial 
vote. 
  Appropriate orders were given to the head of the office of 
the Duma Andrey Voikov. 
  The voting is scheduled for Friday morning when a plenary 
session is to begin at 9 a.m. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41143 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov121_c_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-121 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vote Prompts `Fiery Diatribe' From Rybkin </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vote Prompts `Fiery Diatribe' From Rybkin </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2306063094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 23 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> MK2306063094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Yelena Kolokoltseva report under the "Boycott" rubric: </F>
"Ivan Rybkin Shouts at Absentees. The Upper Chamber Does Not 
Want To, the Lower One Cannot Approve the Budget"] 
  [Text] At yesterday's plenary meeting Ivan Rybkin, speaker 
of the lower chamber, raised his voice to a shout and ordered 
that deputies on trips be recalled, the scheduled State Duma 
visit to The Hague be canceled, and all deputies except for the 
sick come to work by 0900 hours on Friday. The speaker's fury 
stemmed from parliament's failure to adopt the 1995 [as 
published] federal budget at the third reading. Deputies voted 
three times, and in the second vote the budget had every chance 
of being approved -- it fell short by only four votes, which 
could admittedly have been supplied by the 
deputies-cum-government members currently out of town. 
  Nothing seemed to foreshadow such an outcome. After a fairly 
sluggish discussion of the agenda (the deputies did not even 
react to an enticing proposal to dismiss Andrey Kozyrev, who 
signed the treaty on partnership with NATO yesterday), the State 
Duma proceeded to approve the budget it had already given its 
second reading. Things were taking their normal course, but 
somehow lethargically as if in a slow-motion picture: Budget 
Committee Chairman Zadornov had the floor, Deputy Finance 
Minister Petrov followed him, a vote was held -- and there you 
go, the budget was rejected by a margin of 31 votes. The 
deputies voted once again -- another failure. During the break 
the factions left for a conference, the State Duma Council met, 
and acting Finance Minister Sergey Dubinin was summoned. 
However, his arguments that the Central Bank cannot give credits 
and that there will be no money to pay for deliveries to 
northern areas, the harvest, and so forth did not convince the 
people's representatives -- the budget fell 43 votes short of 
approval. It was then that Ivan Rybkin delivered a fiery 
diatribe and demanded that those "stuck in the smoking room, 
giving interviews, and so forth" be brought back. However, the 
only person to respond -- and even he only responded by 
telephone -- was Anatoliy Sliva, chairman of local 
self-government committee, who said that, though he was sick, he 
would come to the Friday meeting to attend the fourth vote on 
the budget. 
  It is doubtful, however, that all deputies will follow 
Anatoliy Sliva's noble impulse -- on Friday the next match of 
the Russian soccer team at the World Cup will be aired on 
television during the daytime. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41144 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov121_c_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-121 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Debates Yeltsin's Organized Crime Decree </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Duma Debates Yeltsin's Organized Crime Decree </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206180794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1525 
GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2206180794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Taranov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 22 Jun--Today the Russian State Duma 
examined the issue of the Russian president's decree "On Urgent 
Measures to Protect the Population From Gangsterism and Other 
Kinds of Organized Crime". In his report, Viktor Ilyukhin, 
chairman of the Security Committee, said that the most resolute 
struggle against crime should be mounted. He believes, however, 
"illegality cannot be used to fight illegality." 
  In his address to State Duma deputies, First Deputy Interior 
Minister Mikhail Yegorov noted that the painful process of 
forming new economic structures is under way in the country. 
"The law enforcement bodies know very well who the leaders of 
the criminal world are," the general said. "And, in this 
respect, the presidential decree makes it possible to deal with 
them. We are not going to detain anybody for 30 days. Give us 
at least a month. I assume the entire responsibility for 
implementing the decree." 
  Finally, the State Duma adopted a decision to: 
  1. Draw the Russian Supreme Court's attention to the need to 
observe the Russian Constitution and relevant legislation when 
examining specific criminal cases; 
  2. Confirm the fact that norms of the Code of Criminal 
Procedure are fully in force in the Russian Federation; 
  3. Have the State Duma Committees for Security, Legislation, 
and Legal and Judicial Reform submit to the State Duma for 
examination within two weeks the following draft federal laws: 
"On Combating Organized Crime"; "On the Fight Against 
Corruption"; "On State Protection for Victims of Crime, 
Witnesses, and Other Persons Assisting Legal Proceedings"; "On 
State Protection for Judges, Officials and Law Enforcement 
Bodies"; "On Russian Federation Counterintelligence Bodies"; "On 
the State of Emergency"; "On Keeping in Custody People Suspected 
and Accused of Crimes"; "On the Russian Federation 
Constitutional Court"; and "On State Service"; 
  4. Invite the Federal Assembly's Federation Council, the 
president, and the Russian Government to participate in debating 
and improving the above laws in order to speed their passage 
through the Russian Federal Assembly and their signing by the 
Russian president. 
  5. Recommend to the Russian president to refrain from 
bringing into force Decree No. 1226 of 14 June 1994 "On Urgent 
Measures for Protecting the Population From Gangsterism and 
Organized Crime" in order to bring it in line with the Russian 
Constitution and to submit a draft criminal code, draft code of 
criminal procedure, and draft code of criminal execution of the 
Russian Federation to the State Duma as soon as possible. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

