<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Duma Votes To Raise Minimum Wage </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    State Duma Votes To Raise Minimum Wage </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206172094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1459 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2206172094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 22 TASS--Russia's minimum monthly wage 
will rise to 20,500 roubles (about ten USD) from 14,620 roubles. 
The corresponding law, taking to effect from July 1, was 
adopted today by the State Duma (lower house) of the Russian 
parliament. 
  The new minimum wage in the state-run sector will be 
provided 
by corresponding budget sources, whereas all other companies and 
agencies should ensure it from their own sources, the law stated. 
  Labour Minister Gennadiy Melikyan, speaking before the Duma, 
noted that only 3.5 per cent of Russians live off the minimum 
wage. According to the minister, the survival minimum (what the 
West calls poverty line--TASS) for Russia amounts now to 72 
thousand roubles. 
  The new law is to be submitted for approval to the 
Federation 
Council (upper house) of the Russian parliament. 

</TEXT>

