<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Partners in European Security' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Partners in European Security' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2306085794 Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI in Russian 23 Jun 94 p 
1 </F>

<F P=103> PM2306085794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKIYE VESTI </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Pavel Shinkarenko: "We Become Partners in </F>
European Security"] 
  [Text] In Brussels yesterday at the NATO headquarters 
Russian Federation Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev signed the 
framework document of the "partnership for peace" program and 
the bilateral "Russia-NATO" protocol which proclaims at official 
level the sides' agreement to cooperate in the political, 
military, and military-technical fields. 
  Commenting on this event, the head of the Russian Foreign 
Ministry explained that it is a case of the two programs 
starting simultaneously. One of them, "Russia-NATO," reflects 
Russian priorities in cooperation with the alliance while the 
other, NATO's "partnership for peace," reflects the North 
Atlantic Alliance's proposals which have been accepted by the 
Russian side. The two programs, Kozyrev said, do not contradict 
each other but on the contrary supplement each other. 
  It is symbolic that the ceremony of Russia's accession to 
the 
"partnership for peace" program took place 22 June, on the 
anniversary of the start of the Great Patriotic War, one of 
whose results was the world's division into two opposing camps. 
Having become the West's partner in European and global 
security, Russia has thus overcome one more frontier on the path 
toward a civilized world community. Here, NATO Deputy Secretary 
General Sergio Balanzino stressed, Russia is the only superpower 
in Europe and it will continue to retain this status. Without 
it it is impossible to achieve success in building a new, secure 
Europe. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

