<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Says Russia in No Hurry To Join NATO </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Says Russia in No Hurry To Join NATO </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206154794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1429 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2206154794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature] </F>
  [Text] Russia does not rule out that at a certain stage it 
may join NATO, just like any other country, however, it believes 
it should be in no hurry to do so, Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev has said. He was speaking at a news conference in 
Brussels following his talks with the U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher. 
  Kozyrev said that "Partnership for Peace" was enough to 
develop cooperation with that alliance. 
  Kozyrev said that at his talks with the U.S. Secretary of 
State six questions were discussed -- President Yeltsin's visit 
to the United States scheduled for late September, the G-7 
summit in Naples next month, the UN Security Council's draft 
resolution on North Korea's nuclear program and situations in 
Latvia and Estonia, and Bosnia. 
  Kozyrev said that the sides had proved to have close or 
identical attitudes to all fundamental aspects of the North 
Korean nuclear problem. "Our representatives in New York are 
still to do some editing", Kozyrev said. 
  As he answered questions, Kozyrev warned that sanctions 
against North Korea would be inevitable in 30 days unless that 
country took positive steps to meet the international community 
half-way. He said North Korea should be helped by convening an 
international conference. 
  About the Baltic countries the Russian Foreign Minister said 
Latvia had adopted laws that do not hold water. 
  As for Estonia, there might be an early agreement on the 
withdrawal of troops from that country on the condition Tallinn 
displayed goodwill. 
  About Bosnia Kozyrev said that the liaison group was to meet 
in session on June 28 to produce a plan for a settlement in 
Bosnia. 
  He said that the liaison mission would use the stick and 
carrot policy towards the warring factions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

