<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin in Greece To Sign EU Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin in Greece To Sign EU Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Comments on Agreement </H4>

<F P=102> LD2306064594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0525 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2306064594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 23 June -- Boris Yeltsin described the 
forthcoming signing of the agreement between the Russian 
Federation and the European Union as a first tactical step by 
means of which Russia "comes to Europe." Flying to Greece 
today, where a sitting of the European Union will take place, 
Boris Yeltsin told journalists with satisfaction that henceforth 
discriminatory measures vis-a-vis Russia "when we were not given 
quotas for the export of goods have been overcome." 
  In the Russian President's view, the agreement between the 
Russian Federation and the European Union notes the transitional 
nature of the Russian Federation's economy. The President added 
that in the United States the transitional nature of the Russian 
economy has not yet been recognized and therefore for the time 
being obstacles for Russian goods have not been abolished. The 
President said that the agreement would create a favored 
treatment for Russian goods in Europe. It could already be said 
now that the new parameters of cooperation and partnership will 
make it possible to expand the export of goods from Russia to 
Europe. 
  First of all Boris Yeltsin stressed that the Agreement 
specifies "how much uranium and aluminum Russia will be able to 
sell on the European market." "Previously we were not allowed 
into Europe with these commodities". In this respect the 
President regards his visit as extremely useful for the Russian 
economy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

