<H4>    Comments on Most Favored Nation Status </H4>

<F P=102> LD2306074494 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
0700 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2306074494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Russian President Boris Yeltsin flew 
from Moscow to Greece today. He will attend a meeting of heads 
of state and government of the European Union on the island of 
Corfu. 
  [Correspondent A. Dubnov] Before leaving for Corfu Boris 
Yeltsin answered questions from journalists on relations with 
European countries. According to the president, there was 
discrimination against Russia in earlier times, quotas for our 
goods were limited and our foreign economic proposals were 
ignored, but now there is a whole package of proposals with 
specific dates and figures. Boris Yeltsin noted the European 
community had recognized the fact that there was a transitional 
economy in Russia while the United States had refrained from 
recognizing this. 
  [Begin Yeltsin recording] A most favored nation status in 
trade has been given to Russia in Europe. This is very 
important, too. Russia is only gaining from this. Finally, this 
is, perhaps, the first practical step by which Russia truly 
enters Europe and deservedly becomes a fully-fledged European 
country. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

