<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-121 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin in Greece To Sign EU Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin in Greece To Sign EU Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Deputy Minister Previews Signing </H4>

<F P=102> LD2206160494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1441 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2206160494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: compiled by </F>
Nikolai Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovskiy; edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] On Thursday morning, President Yeltsin is to fly out 
to Greece to attend the meeting of the European Union leaders 
(June 24 and 25). At 10:00, Friday, he is expected to sign the 
agreement on partnership and cooperation between the Russian 
Federation and the European Union in St. George Church in the 
island of Corfu. 
  Russia's Ministry for Foreign Economic Relations told 
Interfax that the agreement was ready for signing. In the 
evening June 23, after the final coordination of the text 
printed in the 10 languages of the signatory states, this 
document will be initialled by the leaders of the delegations 
involved in the talks. 
  Deputy Minister for Foreign Economic Relations Georgiy 
Gabunia announced that the package of the agreement-related 
documents consisted of about 100 pages, including the joint 
declaration and exchange letters. 
  He also said that according to the agreement, the European 
Union would not consider Russia to be a country with a 
state-controlled trade system, but a state with a transitional 
economy. 
  The Ministry's leading expert Maksim Medvedkov told Interfax 
that the agreement had been drafted during intensive talks which 
continued for two years. He also said that serious problems had 
been caused by the European Union's reluctance to ease the 
access of Russian goods to its markets, and by disagreements 
over Russia's uranium exports and the procedure of the European 
Union banks' work in Russia. "These problems have been solved on 
the whole," he said. 
  IF Note: The draft agreement provides for the mutual 
observance of the basic GATT principles with a few exceptions 
reserved for the nuclear materials on which a separate agreement 
will be concluded in 1997. As to the European Union's banks, 
according to the reached compromise, the five banks which have 
been granted the permit to deal with Russian residents, but 
which have not used this right given the Russian president's 
decree on limiting foreign banks' operations (November 1993), 
shall have their rights restored. The rest of the banks will 
carry out limited operations during a lengthy transitional 
period. For instance, the maximum share of foreign capital in 
the Russian banking system will be limited to 12 percent. The 
number of foreign banks' branches will also be limited. 
  Medvedkov said that the agreement on partnership and 
cooperation between the Russian Federation and the European 
Union set forth the terms for the Russian economy's gradual 
integration with the European economic system. It envisages a 
gradual implementation of the principles of freedom of trade, 
services and the movement of capital, and of the establishment 
and operation of companies. The most favored nation status will 
be granted on a mutual basis. 
  IF Note: The European Union is Russia's biggest economic 
partner. It accounts for 35 percent of Russia's trade turnover 
with foreign countries and 36 percent of the Russian exports. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

