<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Foreign Minister Criticizes Act </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Foreign Minister Criticizes Act </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206162394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1522 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2206162394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: By correspondents </F>
Igor Porshnev, S. Kolosova, and others] 
  [Text] Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Sergey Krylov 
described the citizenship act passed in Latvia as inhuman. He 
told Interfax that the act turned numerous residents of Latvia 
into stateless persons, made it impossible for them to become 
citizens and imposed naturalization quotas. 
  He said the law did nothing for the image Latvia was 
striving 
for itself as a stronghold of democracy. 
  Krylov said that the act was aimed against the 
Russian-speaking residents of Latvia. He explained that if it 
became law, Russian- Latvian relations would deteriorate, the 
visit of Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin to Latvia 
would most likely not take place and numerous agreements made 
during the recent visit of Latvian President Guntis Ulmanis to 
Moscow would be in doubt. 
  He did not rule out the possibility that Russia would lift 
Latvia's most favored nation status. 
  Krylov said he did not believe, however, that the 
citizenship 
act would influence the deadline for the withdrawal of Russian 
troops from Latvia. 
  He said that Russia intended to raise the question of human 
rights violations in Latvia in the CSCE and other international 
organizations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

