<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Nazarbayev Explains Reshuffle, `Anticrisis Policy' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nazarbayev Explains Reshuffle, `Anticrisis Policy' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206163294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1530 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2206163294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: No. 118 (608); </F>
compiled by Nikolay Zherebtsov and Andrey Petrovsky; edited by 
Vladimir Shishlin] 
  [Text] President Nursultan Nazarbayev has said in a 
televised interview the latest changes he made to the structure 
of executive government and the personnel reshuffles in the 
cabinet were linked with what he described as a new anti-crisis 
policy developed by the government. 
  President Nazarbayev said the anti-crisis program would be 
discussed in parliament in a few days and then approved by the 
President. 
  President Nazarbayev said the government of Kazakhstan had 
proposed a "team prepared to act on it." He said he had agreed 
with the proposed reorganization of ministries, personnel 
changes to the cabinet and the leadership of some ministries and 
authorities in regions and in the capital 
  President Nazarbayev believes that "new, younger people 
having a good idea of what business and economic reform are 
about have joined the Cabinet". In particular, he emphasized 
the appointment of 40-year-old Kozykorpesh Yesenberlin as 
Chairman of the State Property Committee and 32-year-old 
Galymzhan Zhakiyanov as head of the Semipalatinsk regional 
administration. Both have a record of work in "commercial 
structures." 
  President Nazarbayev said that the government would be given 
carte blanche for 15 months to act on the program, and the 
presidential staff and the president himself would closely 
monitor progress in its implementation. The future of the 
government will be decided upon the end of the term. "If the 
program is not implemented, the Cabinet will resign," President 
Nazarbayev said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

