<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Seeks Human Rights Monitoring of Crime Edict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Seeks Human Rights Monitoring of Crime Edict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206123594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1010 
GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2206123594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, 22 Jun (ITAR-TASS) -- Boris Yeltsin has 
asked Sergey Kovalev, the human rights representative who was 
appointed to that post by the State Duma, to observe the 
implementation of the decree "On urgent measures to protect the 
population from gang violence and other manifestations of 
organized crime", including the examination of complaints from 
citizens. "I hope that you sympathize with the considerations 
which forced me to sign the decree. At the same time, I share 
the apprehensions of the public, the deputies, and your own 
fears that during implementation of the decree threats to 
constitutional human rights could arise," reads a letter by the 
president of the Russian Federation, the text of which was 
circulated by his press service. 
  "I believe that until the relevant federal constitutional 
law 
has been adopted, the representative for human rights should 
proceed in his activity on the basis of the principle of Article 
15 of the Russian Constitution, according to which the 
constitution has direct force and is applicable throughout the 
territory of the Russian Federation," the document notes. "In 
your work you can rely on the assistance of the heads of 
constituent parts of the Federation and of the president's 
authorized representatives." 
  Presidential aide Georgiy Satarov told an ITAR-TASS 
correspondent that within the next few days Boris Yeltsin will 
submit to the State Duma a bill on introducing additions and 
alterations to the Criminal Code and the Criminal Procedural 
Code of the Russian Federation in order to bring the decree on 
combatting gang violence into line with Russian legislation. He 
is participating in today's meeting of the lower house of 
parliament together with Aleksandr Yakovlev, the Russian 
president's authorized representative at the Federal Assembly. 
Deputies are expected to again express their views on the 
decree which has met with a mixed reaction among politicians. 
  Having told an ITAR-TASS correspondent that "Boris Yeltsin 
does not intend to suspend this decree," Sergey Filatov, head of 
the president's administration, added that "if violations of 
human rights are observed in the course of its implementation, 
adjustments may be made to the document. It is not a dogma." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41213 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov121_b_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-121 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Signs Edict To Enforce Human Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Signs Edict To Enforce Human Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206205894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1849 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2206205894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow June 22 TASS - Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin signed a decree on Wednesday to enforce human rights 
guarantees in Russia, the presidential press service said. 
  For the purpose of ensuring the rights and freedoms of 
citizens provided for by the Russian Federation laws "on 
rehabilitation of the victims of political repressions" and "on 
pensions of citizens leaving for permanent residence outside the 
Russian Federation" the president has instructed the government 
to approve within the month the following documents: 
  On return of property illegally confiscated during 
repressions and payment of compensations, on the procedure for 
paying compensations to the victims of political repressions, 
and on the procedure for paying pensions to citizens leaving for 
permanent residence outside the Russian Federation. 
  Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin has been authorised to 
oversee the implementation of the decree. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

