<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Repayments to Foreign Creditors in 1993 Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Repayments to Foreign Creditors in 1993 Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306105894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 0942 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2306105894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In 1993, Russia repaid about $3.6 billion to its 
foreign creditors, and received $1.5 billion from its debtors, 
according to the Central Bank's report for 1993, submitted to 
the State Duma. 
  As of January 1, 1993, Russia owed foreign creditors $74.6 
billion. The spending on servicing the foreign debt in 
accordance with the schedule, coordinated with the 
creditor-countries, amounts to $40.7 billion, which is three 
times greater than the current credit balance. Out of this sum 
$17 billion (including interest) should have been repaid in 
1993; $9.7 billion is the deferred 1993 payments and $14 billion 
-- overdue payments. In real terms, Russia could repay only 
$2.5 billion in 1993. 
  The report also says that in 1993 Russia succeeded to 
persuade the Paris Club to transform part of its foreign debt. 
It reached the agreements on deferring the repayment of DM 
[deutschmarks] 8.5 billion to Germany, $1 billion to the U.S. 
and FRF [French francs] 1 billion to France. Depending on the 
type of the credit, the deferment will range from seven to ten 
years, plus a period of grace of two to five years. 
  In 1993, import tariffs of about 2.5 trillion rubles were 
transferred to the federal budget instead of the estimated 4.5 
trillion rubles, while revenues, gained from centralized 
exports, slightly exceeded 6 billion rubles. The report says 
that in 1993 the hard-currency balance in the Russian banks 
increased by 25 percent, while Russian residents' assets in 
foreign banks increased 2.8 times and amounted to $25 billion by 
the end of the year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

