<H3> <TI>   Iran's Foreign Minister Sends Message on Crimea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Iran's Foreign Minister Sends Message on Crimea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206124394 Kiev UNIAR in Ukrainian 1130 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2206124394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAR </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kiev, 22 Jun -- The Iranian Foreign Minister Dr. 
'Ali Akbar Velayati has sent a letter to Ukraine's Foreign 
Minister Anatoliy Zlenko concerning the developments in Crimea 
following a decision by the autonomy's Supreme Council to 
restore the Crimean Republic's Constitution of 1992. 
  "The Islamic Republic of Iran is convinced," the letter 
stresses, "that this problem must be solved on the basis of full 
adherence to the principles of international law: Respect of 
sovereignty, territorial integrity and inviolability of borders, 
nonviolent conflict resolution, and noninterference in the 
states' internal affairs." The author of the letter noted that 
the "Crimean issue" was Ukraine's internal problem and could be 
resolved peacefully. Dr. Velayati stressed that Iran strived to 
achieve the above goal by means of mutual trust and peaceful 
coexistence. 

</TEXT>

