Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Finance Minister: Foreign Debt Equals $6 Billion </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Finance Minister: Foreign Debt Equals $6 Billion </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2206144694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1315 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2206144694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukraine's debt to Western creditors and former 
Soviet republics stands at $6 billion, Ukrainian Deputy Finance 
Minister Boris Sobolev told INTERFAX-Ukraine. 
  He said that this sum includes credits received and already 
used, as well as "the difference between Ukrainian exports to 
these countries and imports from them." The debt to the CIS 
countries slightly exceeds $4.3 billion, including $2.7 billion 
to Russia, $693 million to Turkmenistan, $28 million to Moldova, 
and $1.3 million to Kazakhstan. 
  The debt to Western countries mostly consists of the 
commitments against the export credits extended to Ukraine by 
the U.S., Germany, and the European Union. 
  Sobolev announced that the total amount of Western credits, 
used by Ukraine stood at about $1 billion. In addition to this, 
Kiev concluded agreements on $2.5 billion worth of loans. 
  Sobolev said that Ukraine was not delaying repayment of 
debts 
to Western creditors. He admitted, however, that Ukraine's 
debts to the CIS countries, including Russia, were not being 
paid back regularly. He said that the debt problem was closely 
connected with that of dividing the former Soviet Union's assets 
and liabilities which is still to be solved. 
  A foreign debt department is to be set up at the Ukrainian 
Finance Ministry to monitor the servicing of the debts, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

