<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shevardnadze Hails Russian Peacekeeping Mission </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shevardnadze Hails Russian Peacekeeping Mission </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Receives Yeltsin Message </H4>

<F P=102> LD2206183994 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1730 
GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2206183994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By GIA correspondent for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi, 22 Jun -- Eduard Shevardnadze, the head of 
the Georgian state, has received Vladimir Zemskoy, Russia's 
ambassador extraordinary and plenipotentiary to Georgia, at the 
latter's request. 
  The Russian ambassador handed the head of state a letter 
from 
the Russian Federation president in which Boris Yeltsin 
expresses profound confidence that friendship and cooperation 
between Russia and Georgia will continue for the benefit of our 
states. 
  Eduard Shevardnadze and Ambassador Zemskoy discussed the 
decision to introduce Russian peacekeeping forces into the 
Abkhazian conflict zone. This decision was adopted by the 
Russian Federation Council. The head of state noted that he 
attaches particular significance to this decision. In his 
opinion, this international move by Russia is of historic 
significance, not only for Georgia. The success of this move 
may serve to guarantee stability in Transcaucasia. In that 
event, Russia's prestige in the world will grow considerably, 
because the responsibility taken by an individual country in 
cooperation with an international organization for such a 
serious move acquires the power of positive example for other 
countries. 

</TEXT>

