<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Reiterates Refusal To Suspend Crime Edict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Reiterates Refusal To Suspend Crime Edict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306085094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0803 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2306085094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 23 Jun (ITAR-TASS) -- Boris Yeltsin today 
said a firm "no" to the ITAR-TASS correspondent's question about 
whether the president intends to suspend the edict on fighting 
banditry after the State Duma so recommended. 
  At the same time, in the words of Vyacheslav Kostikov, the 
head of state's press secretary, the Russian president well 
realizes that "there is a question" about violation of human 
rights in the edict. That is why Boris Yeltsin 22 June sent a 
letter to Sergey Kovalev, the Russian federation's 
plenipotentiary for human rights, instructing him to supervise 
implementation of the edict on protecting the population from 
organized crime and promising his personal support in this. 
  In turn, Sergey Filatov, head of the russian president's 
administration, told the ITAR-TASS correspondent: "We do not 
intend to blindly follow the letter of the document, for it is 
not a dogma. If we see that citizens' rights are being flouted 
on the basis of the edict, we shall think about adjusting it." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

