<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Dniester Leader Views Prospect of Relations With Chisinau </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Dniester Leader Views Prospect of Relations With Chisinau </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU2206194294 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 2150 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2206194294 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tiraspol, BASAPRESS, 17/6/1994 -- The negotiations 
between Dniester and Moldovan sides are temporarily suspended; 
the Chisinau officials made a break "to calm the passions" after 
different political forces criticized the signing of the 
Snegur-Smirnov declaration, stated yesterday Valeri Litskai, 
state secretary of the self-proclaimed Dniester Republic, on 
Asket TV in Tiraspol. In his opinion, other reasons for this 
suspension would include the fact that Chisinau is preoccupied 
with the settlement of the Gagauz problem and that the results 
of the presidential elections in the Ukraine are awaited. 
Litskai declared that Moldova speculates on Dniester's 
financial difficulties. Dniester cannot obtain from Russia the 
coupons printed there, thus causing an acute crisis of cash. 
According to him, Russia declared that it would send the 
coupons to Tiraspol when an agreement between Chisinau and 
Dniester leaders is signed. Litskai pointed out that the 
Tiraspol leadership insisted for three weeks that Snegur meet 
Smirnov, but it received no answer. He said that nevertheless, 
the prospects of settling the conflict are favorable and gave as 
example the signing of an agreement between Russia and 
Tatarstan. According to him, the contribution of Russian and 
CSCE mission mediators to the settlement of the conflict has 
been substantial and constructive. Nevertheless, Moldova will be 
a potential enemy for Dniester, as it fortifies its armed forces 
and refuses to demilitarize, stated Litskai. 

</TEXT>

