<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Federation Council Fails To Adopt Anticrime Edict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Federation Council Fails To Adopt Anticrime Edict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406093494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0911 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406093494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Lyudmila Yermakova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 24 TASS--The discussion, started on 
Thursday, of the presidential decree "On Urgent Measures To 
Protect the Population From Banditry and Other Manifestations of 
Organised Crime", did not end with the adoption of any decision 
on Friday. None of four draft resolutions polled the necessary 
number of votes. Neither did the deputies support a proposal to 
form an editorial commission to work out a new document. 
  The Federation Council, according to the Constitution, may 
not turn down or endorse a presidential decree, Issa Kostoyev, 
chairman of the Federation Council Committee on Constitutional 
Legislation and Judicial Matters, told ITAR-TASS. But since 
Boris Yeltsin referred the document to the Federation Council, 
expressing hope that the upper house of parliament "will ensure 
the exercise of necessary measures to enact the decree in the 
regions and constitutent republics of the Federation", the 
deputies began to examine it, Kostoyev said. 
  The legislation committee, upon studying the decree, came 
forward with a draft resolution emphasising that "any measures 
to combat crime should be based on strict observance of Russia's 
Constitution and federal laws." 
  The draft resolution shares the president's concern and 
supports on the whole the resolute measures being taken by him 
to step up anti-crime fight. 
  At the same time the deputies "have to state that the decree 
contains a number of provisions that run counter to the 
Constitution and legislation," Kostoyev said. He believes that 
the contraditions are quite resolvable. "Therefore, in the draft 
resolution we suggested that the acting prosecutor-general 
"ensure strict observance of the rights and freedoms of 
citizens, the norms of the constitution and criminal procecude 
legislation". 
  In view of the fact that the deputies did not accept either 
this draft resolution or three other ones, Kostoyev recalled 
that, according to the Constitution, the presidential decree 
signed on June 14 is already in effect throughout the territory 
of the Russian Federation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

