<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Community Leaders Reject Residence Permit Statement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Community Leaders Reject Residence Permit Statement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2306111494 Tallinn BNS in English 1748 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2306111494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, June 22, BNS -- Leaders of Russian 
community in Estonia don't agree with a statement Nikolay 
Yugantsov, Russian Representative Assembly chairman, and Alexey 
Zybin, the elder of Russian community, released last week. 
  The statement demanded that Estonian authorities give 
residence permits to all persons registered as residents before 
July 1990, except those categories of residents listed in the 
aliens law as ineligible, military retirees among them. 
  Pyotr Rozhok, chairman of Russian community in Estonia's 
committee on Russian citizens' problems and representative of 
Vladimir Zhirinovsky's Liberal Democratic Party in Estonia, now 
issued a counter-statement declaring that his organization 
actually wants permanent residence permits for all non-citizens 
who lived permanently in Estonia before July 1993 when the 
aliens law was adopted. 
  Rozhok claimed Russian community in Estonia had forbidden 
Zybin to speak on behalf of the organization. In his opinion, 
the Yugantsov-Zybin statement actually supported "deportation of 
military pensioners." 
  Today's statement was signed, besides Rozhok, by Zybin's 
deputy, Stanislav Mikhailov, and another Russian Community 
leader, Yuri Kotenkov. 

</TEXT>

