<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-122 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Sees Progress in EU Cooperation Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Sees Progress in EU Cooperation Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306153394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1000 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2306153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondents Yuriy Sizov, Vladimir </F>
Malyshev, and Yuriy Manilov] 
  [Text] Kerkyra (Corfu), 23 Jun -- "Extensive, hard work 
over a year and a half has ended with an intensive burst of 
progress," Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy Churkin told 
an ITAR-TASS correspondent today, replying to a question about 
the significance of the forthcoming signing of the agreement on 
partnership and cooperation between the Russian Federation and 
the European Union [EU]. 
  Different countries, he stressed, have approached the 
establishment of relations with the European Union in different 
ways. Often those relations have been of disadvantage to those 
states. As for Russia, we have taken the path of signing a 
full- scale document which reflects not only Russia's political, 
but also its economic interests. 
  The representative of the Russian foreign policy department 
said that the talks were difficult. The final compromises were 
reached literally over the final weeks of work on the document. 
"We are grateful to our Greek friends," Churkin noted in 
particular, "who, as EU chairmen, have shown commitment and 
energy in ensuring that work was completed on the agreement 
which will be initialled this evening and signed tomorrow by 
Russia's President Boris Yeltsin and the EU leadership." 

</TEXT>

