<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Armed Forces Paper Welcomes `Partnership for Peace' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Armed Forces Paper Welcomes `Partnership for Peace' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2306113394 Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA in Russian 23 Jun 94 p 3 </F>
<F P=103> PM2306113394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow KRASNAYA ZVEZDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Manki Ponomarev: "Russia and NATO Building </F>
Bridges"] 
  [Excerpts] For many years the European continent was split 
by a deep abyss which divided the countries of the East and the 
countries of the West. It used to seem simply impassable -- in 
the political, economic, ideological, and military respects. 
One side was personified by the Warsaw Pact, the other by the 
North Atlantic bloc. 
  But times have changed. There is no longer a Soviet Union or 
a Warsaw Pact. Even the former abyss has disappeared. Russia 
and the Western countries have taken the path of developing 
cooperation. The embodiment of this new era in international 
life was the signing by Russian Federation Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev at NATO headquarters of the Partnership for Peace 
program, adopted by the alliance in January this year. [passage 
omitted] 
  It should be noted that, generally speaking, the path toward 
Russia's entry into partnership relations with NATO essentially 
began at the meeting that Army General Pavel Grachev, the 
Russian defense minister, had in Brussels in May. Subsequently, 
however, the Foreign Ministry virtually took over all the work 
preparatory to the signing of the framework document and the 
final protocol. Defense Ministry representatives were 
effectively eliminated from this work, even though the 
implementation of all the military measures within the 
partnership framework will, naturally, be the responsibility of 
the Russian Armed Forces. 
  Be that as it may, the most important thing is that the 
implementation of the Partnership for Peace program as far as 
Russia and NATO are concerned will be a bridge across that abyss 
which divided Europe until just a few years ago. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

