<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Chernomyrdin Continues U.S. Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Prime Minister Chernomyrdin Continues U.S. Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Comments on Talks, Reactor Shutdown </H4>

<F P=102> LD2306143594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1358 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2306143594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Pavel Vanichkin and Oleg </F>
Velichko] 
  [Text] Washington June 23 TASS -- Russian Prime Minister 
Viktor Chernomyrdin said that they managed to convince the U.S. 
Administration that Russia should be granted the status of a 
country with a transitional market economy. According to the 
prime minister, this was on of the main results achieved as a 
result of the work of the integovernment Russo-U.S. Commission 
for Economic and Technological Cooperation which met in session 
on Wednesday. 
  Late on Wednesday, Chernomyrdin answered journalists' 
questions. He came out for lifting restrictions impeding the 
establishment of normal trade and economic relations between 
Russia and the United States. Chernomyrdin mentioned 
Jackson-Vanik's amendment which is still in effect as one of 
these obstacles. 
  Touching upon the problem of the possible shut-down of 
Russian reactors for the production of plutonium and a ban to 
use them for the production of nuclear weapons, the prime 
minister made it clear that "Russia fulfills its international 
commitments." According to Chernomyrdin, during the talks with 
the American delegation an agreement was reached "on the U.S. 
participation in the construction of special storages on 
Russia's territory." The sides agreed that Russia would shut 
down double-purpose reactors, while the United States, in turn, 
would partially recompense the cost. 
  Chernomyrdin confirmed that President Boris Yeltsin would 
pay 
an official visit to the United States in September, adding that 
third session of the Russo-U.S. commission which is currently 
under way in Washington can be regarded as the first stage of 
the preparation for the Russo-U.S. summit. 

</TEXT>

