<H3> <TI>   UNESCO Official Ends Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNESCO Official Ends Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306202494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1946 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2306202494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Yuriy Kozlov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 23 TASS -- UNESCO Secretary General 
Federico Mayor has ended his visit to Russia today. 
  On the final day of the visit the UNESCO director general 
attended the opening ceremony of a UNESCO bureau in Moscow. 
Mayor pointed out that the opening of the UNESCO bureau became 
possible due to the desire expressed by the Russian Government 
and the UNESCO Secretariat to deepen mutually advantageous 
cooperation. 
  Mayor highly assessed talks he had in Moscow with the 
Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin, Chairman of the Russian Federation 
Council Vladimir Shumeyko and Patriarch Aleksiy II, heads of the 
Russian Ministry for Science and Technical Politics, Culture and 
Education. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS Mayor said that during the 
talks the sides summed up the results of activities aimed at the 
realization of concrete projects included in a memorandum on 
cooperation between Russia and UNESCO. These projects envisage 
support to the Bolshoi Theatre, the Russian State Library and 
the Hermitage. The sides also discussed prospects for the 
development of cooperation in the field of communications, the 
organisation of international conferences, the reform of 
secondary education in Russia and the use of intellectual 
potential of Russian scientists. 
  According to Mayor, UNESCO has allocated half a million 
dollars to support various projects in Russia, predominantly 
connected with the support to research centers, special schools 
and a programme of studying the Russian language. 
  As a result of the talks agreements were reached to hold a 
second world congress on information science and education and 
establish an international department for human rights at the 
Moscow State Institute of International Relations. 
  During his visit Mayor met with representatives of 
intelligentsia, Russian mass media chiefs, the company of the 
Bolshoi Theater and students of the Moscow State University. 
The UNESCO secretary general also took part in the opening 
ceremony of an exhibition devoted to the famous French poet 
Arthur Rimbaud. 
  The UNESCO secretary general was awarded with an Order of 
People's Friendship for his outstanding contribution to the 
development of international cooperation. The award was 
conferred upon him by the Russian President Boris Yeltsin in the 
Kremlin. 

</TEXT>

