<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Intervention in Rwanda Supported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Intervention in Rwanda Supported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306144494 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1355 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2306144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Boris Krivoshey] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 23 Jun -- The sending to Rwanda of the 
multinational forces under French command does not fully meet 
the "classical" criteria for UN peace-keeping, but in conditions 
of the continuing tragedy it is a step that is necessary in 
order to stabilize the humanitarian situation in that country. 
This was stated at a briefing today by Grigoriy Karasin, 
director of the department of information and press of the 
Russian Foreign Ministry. 
  A few days ago the UN Security Council, he noted, adopted a 
decision on sending multinational forces to Rwanda. The core of 
these forces would be made up of a contingent of French troops. 
It is proposed that the French contingent will number about 
2,000 men. All the expenses connected with carrying out this 
operation will be borne by the relevant countries. 
  Russia supported this UN Security Council resolution, 
considering that this decision is an enforced step but an 
essential one in the present circumstances. Here, we proceeded 
from the position that the human tragedy in Rwanda, which is 
unprecedented in its scale, and the continuing extermination of 
the civilian population of this long-suffering country dictates 
the necessity of adopting urgent and commensurate measures 
capable of halting further bloodshed in Rwanda. Moreover, we 
have taken account of the fact that the full deployment of 
additional UN forces will need quite a long period of time," 
Karasin said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

