<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Unaware of New Israeli Proposals to Syria </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Unaware of New Israeli Proposals to Syria </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306172994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1707 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2306172994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Yuriy Tyssovski] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 23 TASS -- The Russian foreign ministry 
knows nothing about possible Israeli proposals to Syria with the 
aim of finding a possible way out of the now suspended 
Israeli-Syrian peace talks, that is how Aleksandr Shein, a 
responsible official of the Near East and Africa department, 
commented upon the latest statements made by Israeli leaders on 
this issue, during a telephone talk with ITAR-TASS. 
  On Wednesday Israeli Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres said 
that 
certain quite interesting proposals have been made to the 
Syrians, in case they are accepted by Damascus, a breakthrough 
can be made in the Arab-Israeli negotiations within the peace 
process framework. The minister, however, did neither clarify 
the essence of those proposals nor named the channels through 
which they would be conveyed to the Syrian capital. 
  Nikolay Tikhomirov, deputy director of the Near East and 
Africa department, in this context noted Israeli Prime Minister 
Yitzhaq Rabin's statement, who had said at a meeting with 
activists of international zionist movement in Jerusalem on 
Wednesday that Israel is not prepared to pay such a high 
"territorial price" for peace, which it paid during talks with 
Egypt, returning Cairo the whole occupied Sinai peninsula. 
Syria's position at the talks with Israel is well-known, 
Tikhomirov emphasised. Damascus is for an unconditional 
exchange of territory for peace. In other words, for 
compeletely returning the occupied Golan Heights and 
establishing peace between the two countries within the 
framework of a comprehensive settlement. It follows from the 
Syrian leadership's statements that they won't go in for 
anything less than this. 

</TEXT>

