<F P=103> LD2306184394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Boris Krivoshey] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 23 Jun -- The edict of President Askar 
Akayev, which is aimed at reducing the emigration of the 
Russian-speaking population from the Republic of Kirghizia 
[Kyrgyzstan], will undoubtedly further strengthen all-round ties 
between Russia and Kyrgyzstan. This was stated today at a 
briefing by Grigoriy Karasin, director of the Department of 
Information and Press of the Russian Federation Ministry of 
Foreign Affairs. 
  "The measures envisaged in this edict," he noted, "meet the 
objective demands of an extensive part of the population of 
Kyrgyzstan half way, are a step in the development of democracy, 
boosting the main rights and freedoms of the country's citizens, 
they take into account the wishes expressed by the Russian side 
with regard to this issue, including on a summit level." 
  The representative of Russia's foreign policy department has 
also expressed the hope that the drafts for the relevant laws 
that have been submitted to the Kyrgyz Supreme Council will be 
approved and the government will take effective practical 
measures to enforce out the president's edict. 

