<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   World Bank Grants $820 Million Credit To Government </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    World Bank Grants $820 Million Credit To Government </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306201494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1933 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2306201494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Pavel Vanichkin, Oleg Velichko] </F>
  [Text] Washington June 23 TASS -- The World Bank will 
provide Russia four credits totalling 820 million U.S. dollars. 
This is the main outcome of the talks held between Russian 
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin and World Bank President 
Lewis Preston on Wednesday evening. The agreements on providing 
these credits were signed by Russian Vice-Premier Aleksandr 
Shokhin and World Bank Vice-President Wilfried Thalwitz. 
  Two of these credits are meant for assisting the development 
of Russia's agriculture sector. These are credits to support 
reforms in agriculture (240 million dollars) and to support land 
reform (80 million dollars). The third credit will be provided 
by the bank for restoring roads (300 million dollars), and the 
fourth for the development of financial institutions (200 
million dollars). 
  After the signing ceremony of the agreements, Viktor 
Chernomyrdin said that Russia plans to create a special federal 
organization which will work with international financial 
institutions. "We requested the World Bank to put pressure on 
countries who are Russia's debtors," he said. "Finally, one 
more important result of the talks was that the World Bank 
president will pay a visit to Moscow," the Russian prime 
minister said. 

</TEXT>

