<F P=100> Regional Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Energy Crisis Forces Shutdown of Urals Power Station </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Energy Crisis Forces Shutdown of Urals Power Station </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406083394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0602 
GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2406083394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Yevgeniy Tkachenko] </F>
  [Text] Chelyabinsk, 24 Jun -- The energy crisis in the 
South Urals is assuming a catastrophic scale. Chelyabinsk 
Oblast's second largest power station, the Yuzhnouralskaya GRES 
[South Urals Rayon power station], has been shut down owing to 
the suspension of gas supplies. Accordingly, the Uraltrak 
joint-stock company, the Chelyabinsk automatic engineering 
works, and a whole series of other large enterprises that have 
failed to pay their debts to the power engineers have been 
completely disconnected from the supply of electrical energy. 
  An ITAR-TASS correspondent was told by Viktor Makhortov, 
chief engineer at Chelyabenergo [Chelyabinsk energy 
directorate], the debt is currently in excess of 400 billion 
rubles [R] and has grown by R50 billion in the past six months 
alone. At the same time, the power workers owe a total of R43 
billion to Uraltrasgaz [Urals gas line]. The association's 
chief engineer regards the situation as deadlocked and may cause 
the South Urals economy to collapse. Indeed, if one imagines 
the electric furnaces at the huge iron-and-steel plants here 
being de-energized or -- God forbid -- the power supply to the 
nuclear complex being suspended, all this threatens far greater 
consequences than just the closure or shutdown of an engineering 
plant. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-41345 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov122_d_94009" </HT>


