<H3> <TI>   Commission on Nuclear Waste Arrives in Vladivostok </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commission on Nuclear Waste Arrives in Vladivostok </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2306121794 Vladivostok Radiostantsiya Tikhiy Okean 
Maritime Network in Russian 1900 GMT 22 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2306121794 </F>
<F P=104>  Vladivostok Radiostantsiya Tikhiy Okean 
Maritime Network </F>

<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Pacific Ocean" Program] </F>
  [Text] The international community focused its attention 
on problems concerning the utilization of liquid radioactive 
waste in the Far East yet again. An international commission 
comprised of leading Japanese and British experts arrived in the 
Maritime Kray capital today. The representative delegation is 
headed by Jun Yamada, deputy chief of Japanese Foreign Ministry 
Department of Nuclear Energy. For three days, experts will hold 
talks with the kray administration, specialists of the State 
Committee for the Supervision of Nuclear and Radiation Safety, 
and the command of the Pacific Fleet. They will also visit the 
Zvezda nuclear submarine repair plant in the city of Bolshoy 
Kamen. The commission intends to apply conclusions drawn from 
the trip and propose to local authorities and fleet command 
methods of utilization of liquid radioactive waste. 

</TEXT>

