<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Notes Left-Wing `Threat' to Democracy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Notes Left-Wing `Threat' to Democracy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306160394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1546 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2306160394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature: Compiled by </F>
Nikolay Zherebtsov, Andrey Petrovsky; Edited by Vladimir 
Shishlin] 
  [Text] According to Ukraine's President Leonid Kravchuk, a 
threat to democracy in Ukraine stems from some increasingly 
aggressive left-wing forces. 
  In a televised address Wednesday [29 June] night, he 
denounced what he described as madness in Ukraine and called for 
efforts in support of democracy in the Republic. 
  He also warned that the struggle for power in Ukraine could 
lead to disaster and called for an end to extremism. 
  He emphasized that Ukraine was pursuing the course, chosen 
at 
the referendum of 1 December 1991, when more than 90 pct of 
Ukraine's citizens favored independence. 
  Kravchuk said he believes there is nothing more important 
than to create an incentive for production and development. 
  At the same time, he regretted that no effort was currently 
being spared to set the top bodies of power at loggerheads and 
find contradictions between the president, the premier, and the 
parliament's speaker. 

</TEXT>

