<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Deputies Seek To Strip Meshkov of Powers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Deputies Seek To Strip Meshkov of Powers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306171794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1539 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2306171794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President of Crimea Yuriy Meshkov has described as 
unacceptable and provocative parliamentary discussions of a bill 
intended to suspend the presidency law until a local 
Constitutional Court has been formed. 
  The bill put on the agenda of a parliamentary session in 
Simferopol on Thursday [23 June] follows a resolution of 14 June 
stating that many of the president's decrees were out of line 
with Crimean legislation. 
  Speaking in parliament, Meshkov said the Supreme Soviet was 
out for a stand off with the president under the mask of demands 
for compliance with the Constitution and laws. He said the 
current situation was far too serious to raise the question of 
stripping him of presidential powers. 
  Meshkov sees the parliament's action as an attempt to try to 
put itself above the people of Crimea who elected him as head of 
state in keeping with the Constitution. 
  However, the deputies are most likely to pass the law, 
albeit 
in a softer form, leader of the Crimean Tatars' faction in 
parliament Refat Chubarov told INTERFAX-Ukraine. He described 
what was happening as an attempt by the Russia faction which 
backed up Meshkov during the presidential election to put him in 
his place. 
  As discussion continues, a conciliatory group was elected to 
work out a final resolution. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

