<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Welcomes Russia's Joining Partnership Program </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Welcomes Russia's Joining Partnership Program </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306170494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1539 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2306170494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Ukrainian Defense Minister Vitaliy Radetskyy has 
welcomed Russia's joining of the NATO Partnership for Peace 
program. He was speaking at a news conference in Kiev on 
Thursday [23 June]. 
  Concerning Ukraine's participation in the NATO program 
Radetskyy said that the Ukrainian army was going to participate 
in several NATO exercises within the framework of military 
cooperation. For instance, one company will take part in an 
exercise in the United States and one platoon will be involved 
in an exercise in Belgium this autumn. 
  Ukraine joined NATO's program last February. Radetskyy said 
that financial constraints were the sole brake on contacts under 
the Partnership for Peace plan. 
  Radetskyy was evasive when asked about statements by the 
Ukrainian parliamentary speaker that a joint command of the 
Ukrainian and Russian fleets in the Black Sea was a possibility. 
  Radetskyy believes that the Black Sea Fleet problem is the 
business of governments and parliaments while "the military must 
execute decisions made." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

