<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Accords Reached at Abkhaz Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Economic Accords Reached at Abkhaz Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306165394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1013 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2306165394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Irina Shchegoleva] </F>
  [Text] Sochi, 23 Jun -- The Georgian and Abkhazian sides 
will ask the peacekeeping forces to speed up the mine clearing 
operations in the area where the pylons of the Inguri GES 
[hydroelectric power station] power transmission lines are 
situated. The pylons have been damaged as a result of recent 
subversive operations. 
  Feliks Kovalev, Russian special envoy, told an ITAR-TASS 
correspondent today that an accord to this effect was reached in 
the course of the second session of the Georgian-Abkhazian 
coordinating commission in charge of economic issues, held with 
the participation of the Russian Federation and UN 
representatives in Sochi. 
  "We also asked the Abkhazian delegation to lift the 
restrictions on power supplies for Georgia, introduced by the 
Abkhazian side as part of a package of sanctions," Feliks 
Kovalev further said. 
  The session also examined issues of restoring the power 
supply lines that cross the territory of Abkhazia. According to 
the Russian diplomat, an accord was reached to set up a group of 
experts that will estimate the extent of damage done to the 
power supply lines. 
  According to Feliks Kovalev, "certain difficulties emerged" 
during the discussion of the restoration of through road and 
rail services. 

</TEXT>

