<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   No Candidate Gains Majority of Votes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    No Candidate Gains Majority of Votes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306223094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 2149 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2306223094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by BELINFORM correspondent Vladimir Glod -- TASS] </F>
  [Text] Minsk, 24 June [date as received] -- More than 77 
percent of the electorate took part in the presidential 
elections in the Republic of Belarus. Announcing the first 
preliminary information to a BELINFORM correspondent, the 
Republic's central electoral commission made one thing clear: 
One can conclude from the data coming in that none of the 
candidates has secured the necessary number of votes. 
  At present, one can only talk of an indicated preference for 
two candidates: About 30-32 percent voted for Aleksandr 
Lukashenko, and 24-26 percent voted for Vyacheslav Kebich. The 
remaining four candidates lag significantly behind, and the 
order of preference for them is: Zenon Poznyak, Stanislav 
Shushkevich, Vasiliy Novikov, and Aleksandr Dubko. 
  The highest voter activity was recorded in Brest oblast, 
where over 83 percent of the eligible citizens went to the 
polling stations. The most passive people were in Minsk, where 
the figure was 69.3 percent. 
  The central electoral commission expects to give the 
preliminary results at about 0700 [0300 GMT] in the morning, 
Moscow time. 

</TEXT>

