<H3> <TI>   Karimov Cited on Relations With Turkey </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karimov Cited on Relations With Turkey </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306121794 Tashkent Radio Tashkent Network in Uzbek 1000 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2306121794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tashkent Radio Tashkent Network </F>
<F P=105>  Uzbek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Uzbek President Islam Karimov left for Turkey today 
on an official state visit. Before his departure, answering a 
journalist's question, our country's leader said: 
  [Begin Karimov recording] After achieving our independence 
and sovereignty, small but noticeable changes are taking place 
in our policy and life and also in international and interstate 
ties and in politics. From this point of view we are 
establishing contacts with many countries including the small, 
the powerful, and the large, but we will be looking at how these 
countries see us, how close they are to us, how close their 
people are to us. 
  From this point of view Turkey is very close to us. [words 
indistinct] The people of Turkey, the Turkic peoples are very 
close to us. Their language and their heart but primarily their 
religion and their destiny are very close to us. [words 
indistinct] 
  Our relations with the Turkish leaders, public, and 
entrepreneurs are not bad and are currently developing well. 
For example, there are more than 100 joint enterprises and 
organizations [in Uzbekistan]. We must, however, be frank that 
there are forces who want to damage these ties, these close and 
friendly relations and it would be wrong to ignore these. For 
this reason such forces must be controlled and we must look at 
our relations with this close and strategically [word 
indistinct] state on the basis of a long sighted policy. 
  Raising economic and political ties with this state to a new 
level is the reason for our current visit. From this point of 
view I believe that Turkey looks at us with the same wish and 
hope and I think that this visit will raise our relations with 
Turkey to a new level -- primarily it will be in the interest of 
Uzbekistan and the people of Uzbekistan. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

