<DATE1>  23 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Counterintelligence Chief Supports Edict on Crime </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Counterintelligence Chief Supports Edict on Crime </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306150194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1428 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2306150194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Director of the Federal Counterintelligence Service 
Sergei Stepashin voiced his support for the presidential decree 
on urgent measures to combat organized crime. 
  Addressing the Collegium of the Prosecutor-General's Office 
on Thursday, he said that without going into legal assessments 
of the methods of implementing the presidential decree, he fully 
supported the political decision to pass it. 
  He said that the problem lay in the fact that foreign 
special 
services are trying to penetrate into Russian criminal 
structures, establish control over them and use them to the 
detriment of Russian interests. He also pointed out that making 
use of the undefined status of Russian state borders, the 
national security services of the Baltic states and other 
republics "have established contacts with Russian criminals for 
intelligence purposes. 
  He said that a joint directive would be sent to the Russian 
power ministries' territorial bodies in which the disputed 
provisions of the decree will be brought into line with current 
laws. 
  He announced that the Russian president was considering a 
draft decree on the restoration of the investigation department 
in the Federal Counter-Intelligence Service. According to his 
sources, the decree will be signed soon. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

