<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Conference Participants Differ on Crime Edict </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Conference Participants Differ on Crime Edict </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306140594 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1340 GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2306140594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] [Correspondent T. Aldoshina] Acting 
procurator-general Aleksandr Ilyushenko said today that by using 
criminal terrorist methods, the criminal formations operating on 
Russian territory have essentially taken over the streets, 
towns, and populated localities. 
  [Ilyushenko] Their barefaced insolence and impunity are 
creating an atmosphere of fear and helplessness in society. 
  [Aldoshina] Over the first five months of this year, 
1,094,000 crimes were registered, 216,000 of them serious 
crimes. In the view of participants in the extended sitting of 
the procuracy's collegium, the federal program for combatting 
crime and the president's edict on protecting the population 
from gang violence should put an end to organized crime. 
However, the document is controversial. 
  [I. Kostoyev, chairman of the Federation Council's Committee 
for Constitutional Legislation] It is quite clear that the 
president's edict contradicts the constitution and a number of 
federal laws. 
  [Aldoshina] Issa Kostoyev believes, however, that the actual 
state of affairs must be borne in mind and, given the outburst 
of gang violence, that the edict should be used as an interim 
legal enactment. Those assembled in the hall believe that it is 
now a question of who will bring whom down first, the state or 
the mafia? And the law enforcement bodies intend to demonstrate 
their strength whatever happens. 
  [Sergey Stepashin, director of the Russian Federal 
Counterintelligence Service] I am in favor of the violation of 
human rights, if the person involved is a bandit and criminal. 
There can be no alternative here. 
  [Aldoshina] The only person who objected to this stance was 
Sergey Kovalev. 
  [Sergey Kovalev, chairman of the Russian Federation 
President's Human Rights Commission] Human rights exist. If you 
are in favor of violation of the rights of the criminal, you are 
in favor of the violation of human rights. This axiom is known 
worldwide. 
  [Aldoshina] As the acting procurator-general explained 
today, 
only the Constitutional Court can revoke the president's edict. 
However, the participants in the procuracy collegium are fully 
determined to use this document to bring the full punitive force 
of the law to bear and achieve a real breakthrough in the crime 
situation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

