<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovskiy Threatens To Leave Social Accord Treaty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zhirinovskiy Threatens To Leave Social Accord Treaty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2406104194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1030 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2406104194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 24 TASS -- The leadership of the Liberal 
Democratic Party of Russia (LDPR) examines the issue of 
withdrawing from the Public Accord Treaty, LDPR leader Vladimir 
Zhirinovskiy told a news conference at the Russian parliament 
lower house on Friday. 
  According to Zhirinovskiy, the LDPR is forced to do this "by 
the present course of the Russian leadership" which "does not 
justify the hopes" of Liberal Democrats for resolving problems 
facing the country. 
  Speaking about policy towards former Soviet republics and 
other foreign countries, Zhirinovskiy called for closing down 
some sections of the state border and for expelling from Russia 
those who have no entry visas. He demanded that Russian troops 
be pulled out of all "flash points". 
  "No contacts with NATO and no joint war games," thundered 
the 
LDPR leader. 
  Turning to domestic problems, he favoured an immediate 
suspension of "privatisation a la Chubays". Zhirinovskiy said 
that the LDPR parliamentary group did not vote on Friday for the 
1994 federal budget which, in the group's opinion, is "an 
anti-social budget". 
  Zhirinovskiy disfavoured proposals on extending powers of 
the 
president and parliament. "We cannot adopt this version," the 
LDPR leader said at the lower house, giving, however, no 
explanations why his group favours this position. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

