<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Addresses Journalists' Congress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shumeyko Addresses Journalists' Congress </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2306204394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1517 
GMT 23 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2306204394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Ivanova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 23 Jun -- The intention of Russian 
journalists to adopt a code of professional ethics "inspires 
confidence that democracy is alive and kicking," Federation 
Council Chairman Vladimir Shumeyko said when speaking today at a 
congress of Russian journalists. Stressing that the political 
freedom of the media is sealed in the Constitution, he 
reaffirmed that the economic situation places dependence on 
journalists. Many political groups, who, via financial 
institutions and banks are trying to take the press in hand, are 
rushing to take advantage of this. According to Vladimir 
Shumeyko, they are being driven by the desire to create their 
own image in the run-up to the presidential elections. There 
are a large number of claimants to the seat of president. 
  The head of the Federation Council said that the upper 
chamber of parliament stands for protecting the rights of 
journalists and their economic independence. He said that the 
state is committed to giving tax benefits to the "fourth 
estate," for "one cannot equate the media with consumer goods 
production." 
  Vladimir Shumeyko also noted that it is precisely 
journalists 
who must become one of the creators of a nation concept which 
would unite Russians, would fill a spiritual vacuum and inspire 
confidence in tomorrow. With such an idea, economic problems 
would be solved much more effectively, Vladimir Shumeyko said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

